posts.content:
"You may have mouth cancer. It's a 50/50 survival rate & the life expectancy is 18 months."

(spoiler alert, I'm ok)

I was just going in for a small lump in my lip. No biggie. After spending 30 seconds digging around in my mouth my doctor looked straight into my eyes and delivered the potential diagnosis.

I was shook to my core.

I tried to be brave, but the second I got to my car I burst into hysteria, unsure how to tell my family or what to do next. What. The. Actual. F?

After a few phone calls I was able to get a same day appointment with a specialist (what are the odds). My wife was on her way in to meet me when the new doctor took a look and assured me that I was going to be okay.

An hour later, the lump was removed from my lip. My new doctor was confident it wasn't cancer, and they were sending it off to be tested just in case.

Even though this whole experience only lasted a few hours, it was an emotionally exhausting day & weekend. It really makes you sit back and evaluate what is truly important in this life.

For me: that's spending meaningful time with my wife & my kids. Everything else comes second. A distant second. A very distant second.

I wish these focusing moments could be had a lower cost. But it important to understanding what you truly value and where you want to spend your time.

The secret to building generational wealth isn't starting from scratch.

It's combining these 3 asset classes strategically:

I've acquired 7 companies since 2006, building a $16.5M revenue portfolio.

But the real wealth isn't in businesses alone - it's how you combine different asset classes to create exponential growth.

The wealthiest people understand this formula.

They don't just pick one asset class - they strategically combine three:

1. Business Assets

The foundation of wealth building.

When you buy an existing business, you get:
‚Ä¢ Both tangible and intangible value
‚Ä¢ Working systems and processes
‚Ä¢ Proven cash flow from day one
‚Ä¢ Established customer base

2. Real Estate

Timing is critical here.

Wait until your business generates consistent cash flow, then:
‚Ä¢ Use that cash flow to acquire strategic properties
‚Ä¢ Leverage physical assets as collateral
‚Ä¢ Create stability in your portfolio
‚Ä¢ Build long-term appreciation

3. Intellectual Property

This is what separates the wealthy from the ultra-wealthy:

‚Ä¢ Patents, trademarks, content
‚Ä¢ Passive income generation
‚Ä¢ Unlimited scaling potential
‚Ä¢ No physical limitations

The magic happens when you combine these assets correctly, they multiply each other:

‚Ä¢ Business cash flow funds real estate investments
‚Ä¢ Real estate provides collateral for expansion
‚Ä¢ IP creates new opportunities for both

But there's one important thing you must not forget...

Don't try to do everything at once.

Start with one business. Get it generating consistent cash flow.

Then expand strategically into real estate and IP.

The framework I've shared isn't theory - it's exactly what I've done to build sustainable wealth that:
‚Ä¢ Generates consistent cash flow
‚Ä¢ Appreciates over time
‚Ä¢ Can be passed down generationally

You don't need to start from scratch.

In fact, buying an existing business is often the fastest path to financial freedom.

I have a completely new revenue and GTM playbook we are deploying for sales reps and teams in 2025

The reason most sales and revenue teams aren't getting better, faster?

We only implement "homerun" strategies like new playbooks, new tools, and their revenue support teams don't have a seat at the table on what to fix

Winning sales reps and sales teams are focused on 4 things - that's it:

1. Benchmarked performance: We know our numbers for our GAINS metrics. Pipeline Velocity, Sales Cycle by Stage, Win rate by Stage, NRR, and Rep Productivity

2. Their Revenue Operations and Enablement groups aren't regulated to answering tickets and building reports or trainings the nobody looks at. They are strategically aligned to create incremental wins in the GAINS metrics.

3. The sales reps ALL know their own numbers and have personalized development plans to improve the bottlenecks in their process. Reps can coach themselves.

4. Front line leaders spend less time on pipeline conversations and more time building reps skills to impact the metric the rep is focused on. They stop "checking in on deals" and start "working with Timmy on how we can increase win rate from stage 2 to 3"

Pick ONE  of the above and watch what happens

That's it...andand I go hard on this on the AI Powered Seller Podcast - Episode three drops tomorrow!

comments.commentText:
Pipeline Velocity doesn't "measure" anything...it's purely a forecasting mechanism...and a highly unstable and volatile forecasting mechanism.

You cannot measure past or current performance using a guess about the future, and that's what Pipeline Velocity is....a guess about future events that haven't even happened yet!

How can PAST performance be measured based on make-believe events somewhere off in the FUTURE that have never occurred?

Take nine minutes and watch this video and it'll be 100% clear why you can't use Pipeline Velocity as a "performance metric".

posts.commentAdded: Exciting insights! Focusing on benchmarked performance could truly transform sales success. Cant wait to hear more on the podcast!

Do you know the difference between a network and an audience?


Many people likely believe that their connections and followers
are their network.

How many of your connections do you really know?

A very small percentage.

Many big creators boast those figures and sell the growth.

Have you ever actually thought about their engagement

relative to their following?

200k followers, 1k likes and usually, less than 10% of that comments?

Have you even read through the comments?

The ones that aren't repetitive pod engagements

are just AI completely devoid of real insight.

Is that good engagement?

All that work to build followers and a strong network to have

hardly anyone care to leave their thoughts?

Real genuine engagement onis only dependent on

the quality of connections you establish.

The people that value your POV and consider you as one of their VIPs.

The best creators get greater than 70% comments to likes ratio.

Why?

Because there are real conversations taking place.

Why are the gurus getting 1/10 of their likes as comments?

Because their "networks" are not real.

You can accomplish more with 500 real connections

than they could with 100k followers.

This platform has become the equivalent of a beauty magazine.

-> Photo shopped pictures
-> Manufactured personalities
-> Fabricated success
-> Counterfeit authority
-> Pretend popularity

"Don't read beauty magazines; they will only make you feel ugly."
- Mary Schmich

Remote work matters more now than ever before.

A few weeks ago, I woke up to a massive snowstorm.

It got me thinking:

What happens to employees in companies that refuse to embrace remote work even when natural disasters, family emergencies, or other life events arise?

The answer is stark:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Some businesses shut down entirely, grinding operations to a halt.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Others are severely understaffed, forcing employees to take sick or unpaid days.
3Ô∏è‚É£ And worst of all, some put their people in danger, requiring commutes through unsafe conditions, causing stress, and risking accidents.

This isn‚Äôt just inconvenient‚Äîit‚Äôs irresponsible.

Remote work is no longer a perk‚Äîit‚Äôs a necessity.
‚Ä¢ The benefits extend far beyond personal convenience. Remote and hybrid work models:
‚Ä¢ Prioritize safety: Employees aren‚Äôt risking their lives or well-being for a commute.
‚Ä¢ Increase resilience: Operations continue seamlessly, regardless of external disruptions.
‚Ä¢ Support dedicated work time: Flexibility empowers employees to navigate their responsibilities without sacrificing performance.

With modern technology and tools, most knowledge work can be done remotely. Offering flexibility isn‚Äôt just about attracting top talent; it‚Äôs about creating a sustainable, human-focused workplace where employees can thrive no matter the circumstances.

It‚Äôs time for companies to embrace remote and hybrid work‚Äînot as a trend, but as a foundational part of how we work.

The question isn‚Äôt if your organization should prioritize flexibility. It‚Äôs when.

This post was inspired by a thought-provoking conversation started by, founder of, about the critical need for companies to adapt to the future of work on the morning a snowstorm shut this city down.

What‚Äôs stopping your company from fully embracing remote work?
